I was also warned that this surgery would not fix the spinal stenosis & that I will most likely run into more issues with my spine as time goes on & need more surgeries. So that’s basically it. Just taking it one day at a time. Thanks to those that read all of that. (8/8)

Since the surgery I have gained a lot of feeing back, but my feet especially my left foot are still numb. Currently using a walker to get around. I’ve been told I may never gain the feeling fully back in my feet & I will probably be using a cane for the rest of my life. (7/8)

I underwent emergency spinal surgery to decompress & relieve the pressure on my nerves. Mostly the point of the surgery was to gain feeling in my bottom half. It was the most scary and painful experience of my life. (6/8)

Along with the spinal stenosis I also had a few bulging discs at the bottom of my spine. The discs were shifting and putting pressure on the nerves that controlled the feeling in the bottom half of my body causing me to be paralyzed from the waist down.(5/8)

I couldn’t feel from my waist all the way through my feet & I collapsed on the floor of my bedroom. An ambulance team had to put me on a board and carry me down my stairs & take me to the hospital. (4/8)

Because of the extra pressure on my spine things started to happen with my legs and feet. I had to start using a cane to walk cause I’d lose my balance & fall down a lot.Then on January 10th (So last month) the entire bottom half of my body suddenly became numb.(3/8)

After months of lower back pain I got diagnosed with severe spinal stenosis with degenerative disc disease which means that the bottom of my spine is shrinking & the bones are deteriorating. There isn’t a fix for it. It’s a progressive condition that gets worse over time. (2/8)

I’ve had a lot of inquiries regarding what happened to me this past year that rendered me disabled. So I’m making this thread to explain it the best I can… (1/8)
